{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"79eb60d3-5c20-40ef-8019-c3cb47532993","content":"For .NET 8 on Windows, **`dotnet-trace`** is the best starting point — it's lightweight, .NET-aware, and doesn't require extra installs beyond the .NET SDK.\n\n### Collect a CPU trace\n\n```powershell\n# Install the tool (once)\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n\n# Find your process ID\ndotnet-trace ps\n\n# Collect a CPU sampling trace (press Ctrl+C to stop)\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can open in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n### If you need OS-level detail too\n\nUse **PerfView** (free, from Microsoft) — it captures both .NET and kernel ETW events:\n\n```powershell\n# Download from https://github.com/microsoft/perfview/releases\n# Then run:\nPerfView.exe collect -ThreadTime -Zip\n```\n\nThis gives you thread-level CPU stacks including kernel time, GC, I/O waits, etc.\n\n### Quick tips\n- **`dotnet-trace`** → fast, easy, .NET-only stacks.\n- **PerfView** → deeper analysis, OS + .NET combined stacks, better for complex issues.\n- Collect for **15–30 seconds** — that's usually enough for a 100% CPU scenario.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"5f8825d6-dc81-4e50-8746-bd400d717519","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a CPU trace for a .NET 8 service on Windows Server. This is a knowledge question, not a code task.","outputTokens":377},"id":"bc2ba1e4-28e5-489c-8290-bb4a2a834c0d","timestamp":"2026-04-04T00:45:47.724Z","parentId":"f79bf611-69a0-4ea1-800f-09b16b44c4cd"}
